{"id":"astro-ph/0306267","submitter":"Wim de Vries","authors":"Wim de Vries (1,2), Bob Becker (1,2), and Rick White (3) ((1)\n  University of California, Davis, (2) IGPP, Lawrence Livermore National\n  Laboratory, (3) Space Telescope Science Institute)","title":"Long Term Variability of SDSS Quasars","comments":"16 pages, accepted for publication in AJ, Sept issue","journal-ref":"Astron.J. 126 (2003) 1217","doi":"10.1086/377486","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We use a sample of 3791 quasars from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS)\nEarly Data Release (EDR), and compare their photometry to historic plate\nmaterial for the same set of quasars in order to study their variability\nproperties. The time base-line we attain this way ranges from a few months to\nup to 50 years. In contrast to monitoring programs, where relatively few\nquasars are photometrically measured over shorter time periods, we utilize\nexisting databases to extend this base-line as much as possible, at the cost of\nsampling per quasar. Our method, however, can easily be extended to much larger\nsamples. We construct variability Structure Functions and compare these to the\nliterature and model functions. From our modeling we conclude that 1) quasars\nare more variable toward shorter wavelengths, 2) their variability is\nconsistent with an exponentially decaying light-curve with a typical time-scale\nof ~2 years, 3) these outbursts occur on typical time-scales of ~200 years.\nWith the upcoming first data release of the SDSS, a much larger quasar sample\ncan be used to put these conclusions on a more secure footing.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Jun 2003 20:48:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0306268","submitter":"Thomas E. C. Merrall","authors":"Thomas E. C. Merrall, Richard N. Henriksen","title":"Relaxation of a Collisionless System and the Transition to a New\n  Equilibrium Velocity Distribution","comments":"25 pages, LaTeX. Accepted for publication in ApJ","journal-ref":"Astrophys.J. 595 (2003) 43","doi":"10.1086/377249","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In this paper, we present our conclusions from the numerical study of the\ncollapse of a destabilized collisionless stellar system. We use both direct\nintegration of the Vlasov-Poisson equations and an N-body tree code to obtain\nour results, which are mutually confirmed. We find that spherical and\nmoderately nonspherical collapse configurations evolve to new equilibrium\nconfigurations in which the velocity distribution approaches a Gaussian form,\nat least in the central regions. The evolution to this state has long been an\nopen question, and in this work we are able to clarify the process responsible\nand to support predictions made from statistical considerations (Lynden-Bell\n1967; Nakamura 2000). The simulations of merging N-body systems show a\ntransition to a Gaussian velocity distribution that is increasingly suppressed\nas the initial separation of centres is increased. Possible reasons for this\nare discussed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Jun 2003 20:52:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
